    bedsidePearl: 'CLOSE: in patients 16–60 with cryptogenic stroke and a PFO carrying high-risk features (atrial septal aneurysm OR large shunt), PFO closure + antiplatelet abolished recurrent stroke vs antiplatelet alone (0 vs 14 events over 5y, HR 0.03, NNT 20). Atrial fibrillation rose to 4.6% but was largely transient periprocedural. Read with RESPECT long-term and REDUCE (same NEJM 2017 issue).',
    bottomLineSummary: 'In 663 patients 16–60 with cryptogenic stroke and PFO with atrial septal aneurysm OR large interatrial shunt, transcatheter PFO closure + long-term antiplatelet reduced recurrent stroke from 6.0% to 0% over mean 5.3-year follow-up (HR 0.03, 95% CI 0.00–0.26, P<0.001; 5-year ARD 4.9 percentage points; NNT 20). Atrial fibrillation/flutter excess 4.6% vs 0.9% (P=0.02), largely transient periprocedural.',
    conclusion: 'CLOSE established PFO closure plus long-term antiplatelet therapy as superior to antiplatelet therapy alone for preventing recurrent ischemic stroke in patients 16–60 with cryptogenic stroke and a PFO carrying high-risk morphology (atrial septal aneurysm or large interatrial shunt >30 microbubbles). Among 663 patients randomized at 32 French and 2 German sites between December 2007 and December 2016, 0 of 238 closure patients had recurrent stroke vs 14 of 235 antiplatelet patients over mean 5.3-year follow-up (HR 0.03, 95% CI 0.00–0.26, P<0.001). The 5-year Kaplan–Meier absolute risk difference was 4.9 percentage points; authors reported NNT 20 (95% CI 17–25) over 5 years. Atrial fibrillation/flutter occurred in 4.6% of closure patients vs 0.9% of antiplatelet patients (P=0.02), with 10 of 11 closure-arm AF cases detected within 30 days of procedure and no AF recurrence over median 4.4-year follow-up, consistent with transient periprocedural irritation rather than durable arrhythmic substrate. Major procedural complications occurred in 5.9% within 30 days. The anticoagulation-vs-antiplatelet comparison (groups 1+3) was underpowered: 3/187 vs 7/174 strokes (HR 0.44, 95% CI 0.11–1.85), not statistically analyzed. CLOSE established the modern criterion that PFO-closure benefit concentrates in patients with high-risk PFO morphology. Together with RESPECT long-term (Saver JL et al., NEJM 2017;377:1022) and REDUCE (Søndergaard L et al., NEJM 2017;377:1033), published in the same NEJM 2017 issue, CLOSE supports AHA/ASA 2021 Secondary Prevention Guideline Class IIa, Level B-R for PFO closure in non-lacunar stroke <60 with PFO and no other apparent etiology. The accompanying NEJM editorial (Ropper AH, NEJM 2017;377:1093) framed the 2017 cluster as a tipping point and emphasized patient selection by PFO morphology rather than the exclusionary cryptogenic label alone. Limitations: open-label design, restricted to high-risk PFO morphology, early administrative enrollment stop, 11 different closure devices pooled, underpowered anticoagulation comparison, no required prolonged ECG monitoring to exclude occult atrial fibrillation.',
